	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>Little progress in first weeks of 2011</h1>

			
			<h4>
												01 March 2011
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>According to press reports, little progress is being made in the WTO agricultural negotiations on the biggest sticking-point – ‘deep differences between the US and large developing countries such as China, Brazil and India over the depth of tariff and subsidy cuts’. These countries ‘have consistently rejected US demands for greater access to their markets as unrealistic and out of proportion to what rich nations are being asked to do in terms of cutting tariffs and farm subsidies.’ They reject US assertions that ‘the terms currently being contemplated in the Doha Round talks are “imbalanced against” the US.’ Some observers have suggested that the US’s recent harsher criticism of Brazil, China and India could be an indication that ‘Washington is “playing hardball”, seeking to maximise what it can get in return for concessions it is still prepared to make’. Alternatively, ‘the US may simply be jockeying for position to avoid being blamed if the talks cannot be revived in any meaningful way.’</p><p>The extent to which dramatic exchange rate movements are complicating the negotiations was highlighted when Brazil’s representative complained that the appreciation of the real ‘had “wiped out” much of the protection afforded by Brazil’s tariffs to its manufacturing sector.’ It was noted that US exports to Brazil had risen 51% since 2010, which was indicative of the trade impact of the appreciation of the real.</p><p>The pessimistic perspective on the prospects for an agreement was implicitly reinforced by the statement of WTO Director-General Pascal Lamy on 2 February 2011, telling WTO ambassadors that ‘bilateral and small group discussions on resolving key differences need to catch up with work among the full membership on refining texts.’ At the Davos ‘mini-ministerial’, those present took the view that 2011 constitutes a ‘window of opportunity’ for concluding the negotiations. However, it was widely recognised that deep differences still needed to be overcome. A coordinated statement from Brazil, China, India and South Africa, released on the same day as the mini-ministerial, called for a strengthening of the ‘development dimension’ of the Doha Agreement on the basis of the July 2008 text. The statement argued that the formulae and figures for subsidy and tariff cuts and exceptions captured in December 2008 draft agreement texts would require developing countries ‘to offer a level of contribution without precedent by any member in any of the previous negotiating rounds’, with this ‘not being reciprocated by developed countries, some of whom still seek further exceptions and flexibilities to continue with their existing trade barriers and trade distorting policies, adversely affecting the developing countries’ interests.’</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
