<a href="http://ictsd.org/i/news/bridgesweekly/99990/" target="_self">http://ictsd.org/i/news/bridgesweekly/99990/</a></p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>The tone of the recent Doha mini-ministerial discussions and statements issued around the meeting, suggest that ACP concerns in the 27 January statement on cotton issues – that development concerns are falling off the table in the final push for an agreement – are held by a wider group of developing country governments (see <i>Agritrade </i>article ‘
<a href="http://agritrade.cta.int/en/Key-topics/WTO-agreement-on-agriculture/News/Cotton-and-the-reassertion-of-ACP-concerns-in-the-Doha-process" target="_self">Cotton and the reassertion of ACP concerns in the Doha Process</a>’, March 2011). It remains to be seen whether the more vocal direct criticisms which have recently characterised exchanges are reflecting preparations for hard-headed negotiations, or are last-minute attempts to ‘shift the blame’.</p><p>If hard-headed negotiations get under way, a critical issue from an ACP perspective will be whether or not the concerns of importance to ACP members will be constructively addressed within the final negotiating push.</p>
		</div>
		
